title: For Sale:  Thompson Machine SG-2 .45
postcontent: When we started the SG project, we decided to build something that no other manufacturer offers; a quiet, tough, mono-core Submachine Gun suppressor that fully and easily disassembles for cleaning (we find this feature to be a necessity due to the large volume of fire and subsequent carbon fouling that subgun cans are subjected to).  The SG-2 (new for 2014) has all of the features of our original SG suppressor and adds more.  It is shorter and lighter than the original SG, features an ultra-strong threadless-tube design, and now uses the same interchangeable thread adapter systems as our popular Isis-2 and QMF-2 series of suppressors.  It is also rated for (and sounds great on) .300BLK rifles and pistols with SUBSONIC ammo.  What this all boils down to is a more compact suppressor with greater adaptability.  The SG-2 is designed to minimize the blowback and ejection port pop that so commonly is the Achilles Heel of suppressed Submachine Guns.  The SG-2 has a very pleasant, low tone and thread adapters are available for every popular subgun, including Macs, Uzis, the TP-9, etc.  Thread adapters for the SG-2 are also available in common pistol-caliber thread patterns as well such as 1/2-28, 1/2-36, 5/8-24, etc.  On top of all these desirable features, the SG-2 is priced to be affordable for everyone with a subgun to put it on.  MSRP is $449.

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P6 W/Nite Sites
postcontent: Stamped on right side:"P6 - NW - 6/82 Stamped on left side: "Sig Sauer made in W Germany" The only difference between the P6 and P225—the P225 (which was adopted by US civilian law enforcement) has a lighter trigger pull, whereas the P6's trigger pull is heavier. The P225 has tritium fixed sights; P6s had fixed sights only. Genuine P225s manufactured for the West German Police will have a "P6" stamp on the right side of the slide. German police pistols can be identified by the hammer, which has small "ear" or "hook". According to section 7.7 of the German manual, the cutout is the Deformationssporn, which means “deformation spur”. This was a requirement of the West German Police for all their pistols, regardless of manufacturer, to alert police armorers if the pistol was dropped on its hammer.This is a German police surplus gun issued NEW in Germany.The SIG P6 is a more compact version of the SIG P220. The Swiss Army wanted semi-automatic handgun, that would provide excellent functionality with a double-action trigger. The 9mm SIG-Sauer P6, debuted with various new and inventive features. It utilized a single column magazine holding eight 9 mm rounds and has a 3.9 in. barrel.A new German police standard, in the mid-1970s, prompted SIG-Sauer to develop a new pistol that met the standard: The SIG-Sauer P225 (known as the P6) and the Heckler & Koch P7. The SIG-Sauer P225 was the least expensive (due mainly to the inventive design) and received the majority of the orders. To be able to manufacture that many handguns, SIG acquired a controlling interest in J. P. Sauer & Sohn in Eckenförde, Germany to manufacture parts. This is also where all P225s were manufactured. The only difference between the P6 and P225 — the P225 (which was adopted by US civilian law enforcement) has a lighter trigger pull, whereas the P6's trigger pull is heavier. The P225 has tritium fixed sights; P6's have fixed sights only. Because of its compact size, the P225/P6 is quite readily usable for concealed carry. In U.S. states where high-capacity magazines were prohibited, the P6/P225 is in high demand.
